| 2. Diagnose-then-fix 4-level enforcement | ADAPT, strong | downgraded | ADAPT, narrow machine-checkable handoff/schema gate only | `.opencode/agents/debug.md:142-159`; `.opencode/agents/debug.md:481-498`; `.opencode/agents/code.md:121-129` |

### EVIDENCE
- [V-014-01] Claim 1 contract-first: The gap is real but overstated. I found strong spec-kit counter-evidence that it already front-loads verification planning and blocks completion without fresh verification: `sk-code` defines Phase 0 research, Phase 1 implementation, Phase 1.5 quality, and Phase 3 verification, with the Iron Law at `.opencode/skills/sk-code/SKILL.md:35-45`; it requires surface verification commands at `.opencode/skills/sk-code/SKILL.md:187-193`; `AGENTS.md` hard-blocks completion unless strict validation/checklist evidence is run at `AGENTS.md:247-251`. The strongest ordering counter-evidence is @code’s pre-implementation checklist: verification command/action must be identified before the first edit at `.opencode/agents/code.md:180-188`. But grep/read did not find a spec-kit mandate for `test-first` or `TDD` in the live spec-kit control files; the prior research’s external-side claim is recorded at `.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/007-gem-team-adoption-matrix/iterations/iteration-005.md:13-14`. So the exact “tests written before implementation” gap is real, but the net-new value is much narrower than “verification enforcement”: spec-kit already enforces verification-before-completion and verification planning-before-edit.
- [V-014-02] Claim 2 diagnose-then-fix: The core diagnose-before-fix behavior is already strongly covered. @debug is explicitly ordered: observe, analyze, hypothesize, adversarially validate, then fix at `.opencode/agents/debug.md:142-159`; hypotheses require root cause, evidence, validation test, and confidence at `.opencode/agents/debug.md:237-260`; Phase 4 must challenge/re-rank before Phase 5 at `.opencode/agents/debug.md:271-303`; pre-delivery checks require root cause evidence, ordered phases, adversarial validation, tests, and debug-delegation ownership at `.opencode/agents/debug.md:481-498`. @code’s surgical-fix mode already expects root cause, regression protection, before/after failing command, and verification evidence at `.opencode/agents/code.md:121-129`. The genuine remaining gap is not “diagnose then fix” but the machine-checked cross-agent handoff: grep found no live `debugger_diagnosis` schema outside the research notes, and the existing `debug-delegation.md` template is narrative placeholders/hypothesis/next steps at `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/templates/manifest/debug-delegation.md.tmpl:77-97`, not a typed `root_cause`/`target_files`/`fix_recommendations` gate. Orchestrator only prompts @debug after repeated failures, never auto-dispatches or pair-plans debugger→implementer, at `.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:560-563`. The prior research’s external-side 4-level claim is recorded at `.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/007-gem-team-adoption-matrix/iterations/iteration-006.md:10-13`.

### REVISED NET-NEW VALUE
Claim 1: Worth a sub-packet only if scoped. Add a “contract/boundary test or executable acceptance check identified before production edits” gate for API/schema/integration changes. Do not adopt universal TDD/test-first as a hard blocker across all spec-kit work.

Claim 2: Worth a smaller sub-packet than originally framed. Keep @debug’s existing 5-phase method; add a typed handoff validation layer only when a debug handoff is passed between agents: required `root_cause`, `target_files`, `fix_recommendations`, confidence/evidence, and reviewer/orchestrator checks that reject absent or contradictory diagnosis objects.

